            "questionText": "<p>A developer is creating a new application for a pet store. The application will manage customer rewards points. The developer will use Amazon DynamoDB to store the data for the application. The developer needs to optimize query performance and limit partition overload before actual performance analysis.<br><br>Which option should the developer use for a partition key to meet these requirements?</p>",
            "explanation": "<p>üìù <u>T√≥m t·∫Øt ƒë·ªÅ:</u></p><ul><li><p>Developer t·∫°o application cho <strong>pet store</strong> ƒë·ªÉ manage <strong>customer rewards points</strong></p></li><li><p>D√πng <strong>DynamoDB</strong> ƒë·ªÉ store data</p></li><li><p>C·∫ßn <strong>optimize query performance</strong> v√† <strong>limit partition overload</strong> tr∆∞·ªõc khi c√≥ actual performance analysis</p></li><li><p>Option n√†o n√™n d√πng l√†m <strong>partition key</strong>?</p></li></ul><p></p><p>‚úÖ <u>ƒê√°p √°n ƒë√∫ng:</u></p><p><strong>A randomly generated universally unique identifier (UUID)</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>UUID</strong> c√≥ <strong>high cardinality</strong> (ƒë·ªô ph√¢n t√°n cao), m·ªói customer c√≥ unique value</p></li><li><p><strong>Evenly distributed</strong> across partitions, tr√°nh hot partition</p></li><li><p><strong>Prevent partition overload</strong> v√¨ data ƒë∆∞·ª£c spread ƒë·ªÅu</p></li><li><p><strong>Optimal query performance</strong> khi access by customer ID</p></li></ul><p></p><p><u>C√°c ƒë√°p √°n sai:</u></p><p>‚ùå <strong>The customer's full name</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>Low cardinality</strong> - nhi·ªÅu customers c√≥ th·ªÉ c√πng t√™n (John Smith, Maria Garcia, etc.)</p></li><li><p>T·∫°o <strong>hot partitions</strong> cho common names</p></li></ul><p></p><p>‚ùå <strong>The date when the customer signed up for the rewards program</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>Very low cardinality</strong> - nhi·ªÅu customers sign up c√πng ng√†y</p></li><li><p>T·∫°o <strong>severe hot partition problem</strong></p></li></ul><p></p><p>‚ùå <strong>The name of the customer's pet</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>Extremely low cardinality</strong> - r·∫•t nhi·ªÅu pets c√πng t√™n (Max, Bella, Charlie, etc.)</p></li><li><p>BAD choice cho partition key</p></li></ul><p></p><p>üîë <u>Tips and tricks:</u></p><ul><li><p><strong>\"Limit partition overload\"</strong> ‚Üí c·∫ßn <strong>high cardinality partition key</strong></p></li><li><p><strong>High cardinality keys:</strong> UUID, email, customer ID</p></li><li><p><strong>Low cardinality keys:</strong> date, name, status, country</p></li><li><p><strong>Hot partition</strong> = nhi·ªÅu data/requests t·∫≠p trung v√†o v√†i partitions ‚Üí performance issue</p></li></ul><p></p><p>üìñ <u>Reference:</u></p><ul><li><p><a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/bp-partition-key-design.html\">Best practices for designing and using partition keys effectively in DynamoDB</a></p></li><li><p><a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/database/choosing-the-right-dynamodb-partition-key/\">Choosing the right DynamoDB partition key</a></p></li></ul>",
