            "questionText": "<p>A company is using Amazon OpenSearch Service to implement an audit monitoring system. A developer needs to create an AWS CloudFormation custom resource that is associated with an AWS Lambda function to configure the OpenSearch Service domain. The Lambda function must access the OpenSearch Service domain by using OpenSearch Service internal master user credentials.</p><p></p><p>What is the MOST secure way to pass these credentials to the Lambda function?</p>",
            "explanation": "<p>üìù <u>T√≥m t·∫Øt ƒë·ªÅ:</u></p><ul><li><p>Company d√πng <strong>OpenSearch Service</strong> ƒë·ªÉ implement audit monitoring</p></li><li><p>Developer c·∫ßn t·∫°o <strong>CloudFormation custom resource</strong> v·ªõi Lambda function configure OpenSearch domain</p></li><li><p>Lambda function ph·∫£i access OpenSearch b·∫±ng <strong>internal master user credentials</strong></p></li><li><p>H·ªèi: c√°ch <strong>MOST secure</strong> ƒë·ªÉ pass credentials ƒë·∫øn Lambda function?</p></li></ul><p></p><p>‚úÖ <u>ƒê√°p √°n ƒë√∫ng:</u></p><p><strong>Use CloudFormation to create an AWS Secrets Manager secret. Use a CloudFormation dynamic reference to retrieve the secret's value for the OpenSearch Service domain's MasterUserOptions. Create an IAM role that has the secretsmanager:GetSecretValue permission. Assign the role to the Lambda function. Store the secret's name as the Lambda function's environment variable. Resolve the secret's value at runtime.</strong></p><ul><li><p>Secrets Manager thi·∫øt k·∫ø cho sensitive credentials management</p></li><li><p>Credentials stored encrypted v√† <strong>kh√¥ng hardcoded</strong> anywhere</p></li><li><p>Lambda retrieve credentials at runtime t·ª´ Secrets Manager - kh√¥ng store trong environment variables</p></li><li><p>Most secure - credentials rotation support, audit logging, fine-grained access control</p></li></ul><p></p><p><u>C√°c ƒë√°p √°n sai:</u></p><p>‚ùå <strong>Use a CloudFormation parameter to pass the master user credentials at deployment to the OpenSearch Service domain's MasterUserOptions and the Lambda function's environment variable. Set the NoEcho attribute to true.</strong></p><ul><li><p>Environment variables expose credentials (visible trong Lambda console)</p></li><li><p>NoEcho ch·ªâ hide trong CloudFormation, kh√¥ng encrypt storage</p></li></ul><p></p><p>‚ùå <strong>Use a CloudFormation parameter to pass the master user credentials at deployment to the OpenSearch Service domain's MasterUserOptions and to create a parameter in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store. Set the NoEcho attribute to true. Create an IAM role that has the ssm:GetParameter permission. Assign the role to the Lambda function. Store the parameter name as the Lambda function's environment variable. Resolve the parameter's value at runtime.</strong></p><ul><li><p>Parameter Store c√≥ th·ªÉ work nh∆∞ng Secrets Manager t·ªët h∆°n cho credentials (rotation support)</p></li><li><p>Secrets Manager l√† best practice cho database/service credentials</p></li></ul><p></p><p>‚ùå <strong>Use a CloudFormation parameter to pass the master user credentials at deployment to the OpenSearch Service domain's MasterUserOptions and the Lambda function's environment variable. Encrypt the parameter's value by using the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) encrypt command.</strong></p><ul><li><p>V·∫´n store encrypted value trong environment variables - less secure</p></li><li><p>Kh√¥ng c√≥ rotation capability nh∆∞ Secrets Manager</p></li></ul><p></p><p>üîë <u>Tips and tricks:</u></p><ul><li><p>\"MOST secure\" + \"credentials\" ‚Üí <strong>AWS Secrets Manager</strong></p></li><li><p>Secrets Manager &gt; Parameter Store cho database credentials (rotation support)</p></li><li><p>Environment variables = less secure (visible, no rotation)</p></li><li><p>Best practice: retrieve credentials at runtime, kh√¥ng store trong env vars</p></li></ul><p></p><p>üìñ <u>Reference:</u></p><ul><li><p><a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/best-practices.html\">Secrets Manager best practices</a></p></li></ul>",
